{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nEpic 716f drained the module-size allowlist to zero — every over-cap module is split and no `src/rebar/**/*.py` exceeds 800 LOC. Retire the grandfathering ESCAPE HATCH so 800 becomes an absolute cap, and LOCK the limit so it cannot be changed through the normal contribution process (only an admin force-submitting past the gate can land a limit change). Per the operator decision this is a CI-gate-in-code mechanism (no Gerrit ACL).\n\nThis is Phase 2a (the enforcement SWAP). It cannot also delete the allowlist/ceilings files: the CI Module-size gate runs from MAIN's workflow against each change's tree, so main's CURRENT (allowlist-based) gate would break reading the deleted `ceilings` file on THIS change's own CI. So 2a rewrites the gate + tests and adds the limit single-source but KEEPS the now-empty allowlist/ceilings files; Phase 2b deletes them once the new gate is live on main.\n\n## What\n\n1. Add `.github/module-size-limit.txt` containing just `800` — the SINGLE SOURCE of the limit, read by both the CI gate and the contract test.\n2. Rewrite the `Module-size gate` step in BOTH `.github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml` and `.github/workflows/test.yml` (same step NAME so the parity test still finds it):\n   a. Read `LIMIT` from the limit file (fail if missing or not a positive int).\n   b. ABSOLUTE cap: fail if any `src/rebar/**/*.py` (excluding `__pycache__`) exceeds $LIMIT. No allowlist, no exemptions.\n   c. LIMIT LOCK: the step does its OWN `git fetch -q origin main` — the CI checkout configures the `origin` remote (the GitHub mirror) and an explicit `main` fetch brings its tip even on a SHALLOW clone (as FETCH_HEAD), so the step does not depend on the checkout's fetch-depth. It then uses `git cat-file -e FETCH_HEAD:<limitfile>` to distinguish: (i) main HAS the file -> read BASE; if BASE != LIMIT, FAIL with a 'must override' ::error:: (the lock); (ii) main LACKS the file -> bootstrap (the file is introduced on THIS change) -> allow. If the `git fetch` itself FAILS, the step emits a `::warning::` (NOT a silent skip) and falls through to the absolute-cap check (the always-on floor). So the lock fail-opens ONLY on a total fetch failure and never mistakes a real base for the bootstrap case.\n   d. MISSING-FILE GUARD: fail if the limit file is absent (guards deletion of the lock).\n   e. The step reads NEITHER the allowlist NOR the ceilings file in EITHER workflow.\n3. Replace `tests/unit/test_module_size_contract.py`: drop the allowlist/ceilings sync assertions; read the cap from the limit file; assert no `src/rebar` file exceeds it and the file parses to a positive int.\n4. Update `tests/unit/test_ci_workflow_parity.py` `_SHARED_GATE_SIGNATURES` to a signature the NEW gate contains in both workflows (`.github/module-size-limit.txt`).\n5. KEEP the (now-empty) allowlist + ceilings files (Phase 2b deletes them) so main's current gate stays green on THIS change's CI.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `.github/module-size-limit.txt` exists and contains `800` (verify: `test \"$(cat .github/module-size-limit.txt)\" = 800`)\n- [ ] In BOTH workflows the gate reads the limit file and reads NEITHER the allowlist NOR the ceilings file (verify, per file: `for f in .github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml .github/workflows/test.yml; do grep -q 'module-size-limit.txt' \"$f\" || exit 1; ! grep -q 'module-size-allowlist' \"$f\" || exit 1; ! grep -q 'module-size-ceilings' \"$f\" || exit 1; done && echo OK` prints OK)\n- [ ] The limit-lock override message is present in BOTH workflows (verify: `for f in .github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml .github/workflows/test.yml; do grep -q 'must override' \"$f\" || exit 1; done && echo OK` prints OK)\n- [ ] The lock uses a self-sufficient `git fetch origin main` + `git cat-file -e FETCH_HEAD` and WARNS (not silently skips) on fetch failure in BOTH workflows (verify: `for f in .github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml .github/workflows/test.yml; do grep -q 'git fetch -q origin main' \"$f\" && grep -q 'cat-file -e FETCH_HEAD' \"$f\" && grep -q 'could not fetch origin/main' \"$f\" || exit 1; done && echo OK` prints OK)\n- [ ] The gate FAILS when the limit file is MISSING (verify: run the gate step against a tree with no `.github/module-size-limit.txt` -> exit 1 with a 'must not be removed' message)\n- [ ] A simulated limit change fails the lock; unchanged passes (verify: the lock comparison with BASE=800 LIMIT=900 -> exit 1 with the override message; BASE=800 LIMIT=800 -> exit 0)\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_module_size_contract.py` asserts no src file over the file-sourced cap and passes (verify: `pytest tests/unit/test_module_size_contract.py -q`)\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_ci_workflow_parity.py` passes with the updated signature (verify: `pytest tests/unit/test_ci_workflow_parity.py -q`)\n\n## Notes\nPhase 2b (follow-up) deletes the orphaned allowlist/ceilings files, prunes the docs/architecture.md offenders table, and updates AGENTS.md — kept separate because the gate must stop reading those files (this change) BEFORE they can be deleted. E5: the gate is shell (oracle = running it against crafted trees, per the ACs); the contract + parity tests are the Python oracle. The lock's live cross-commit behavior (main-has-file -> fires) is exercised end-to-end by this change's own Verified run and by every subsequent change."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784419020849012001,"uuid":"bdf5397a-272d-4365-a13f-da490b73a99b"}